Hi, I've been emailing with the sishelp team and they're saying that they are looking into the technical issue, but that the EECS department is the one that would initiate any corrective action / manage their own enrollments. However, on here, the EECS department is saying that they do not know how it is going to be resolved and that it is up to the programmers for the Cal Central team. This is rather worrisome. If this bug is indeed an issue, how will it be resolved?

Hi, I've also been in contact with the EECS department. I've tried to contact sishelp but I haven't been getting responses from them. 

Proposed Solution:

Query a list of all the students who bypassed the waitlist via the swap feature, and provide it to the EECS department. Anyone who enrolled after the 80th student enrolled should have gone to the back of the waitlist and should not have been able to enroll, so querying such a list should be straightforward for anyone with the appropriate access to the database, e.g., pull a list of students who enrolled into cs194-129 with enrollment timestamp after the timestamp for the 80th student. Provide the list to EECS, and EECS can move those students to the back of the waitlist.  

Data Fix vs. Bug Fix:

I think we should push for them to fix the data rather than the bug at this point because the data fix is more time urgent than fixing the bug. Fixing the bug in CalCentral enrollment system would not have any benefit for anyone until the next Phase I sometime in the summer when people are enrolling for Fall 2018 classes. But Phase II is about to start and it's in everyone's best interest for the data fix to be done as soon as possible. Obviously the bug fix on the actual swap feature should also be addressed but as mentioned above, the urgency of that is now pretty low and that could be handled any time in the next few months without any additional negative impact to students. Probably should have a separate tickets for the bug fix and for the data fix/request. 

Update & Background on my ticket:

I asked sishelp if they could either fix the data or provide a list of the affected students to the EECS department so that the EECS dept could un-enroll the people who enrolled illegitimately via the swap function. I talked to Michael in the EECS department via email and he said the EECS department cannot lookup the list of the students to un-enroll because they only have the ability to look up the enrollment timestamp for people one at a time, which would obviously take way too much time for someone to do and they are swamped with enrollment stuff right now so it's not feasible. But I think a good compromise is for the technical team (sishelp) that has access to the database to write a quick query to pull such a list of students and provide it to the EECS department. Michael said he'd be on board with that option. So I think we should try to figure out the best way to push for that solution. Would it come from us, the affected students, or would it be best for the EECS department to request the information? 

I called sishelp today and they said my ticket was forwarded to the Office of the Registrar. They updated the priority of my ticket from low to high. I'm not sure if the Office of Registrar now being responsible for the ticket is progress or not (don't know if they will be able to handle the proposed data fix). I'm trying to contact the Registrar office right now to find out what their take on this is.
What did they say?

Person I spoke with at the Office of Registrar wouldn't give me any information, just kept saying the person who the ticket is assigned to might get back to me once they get to the ticket. 

If anyone reading this is on the waitlist please enter a ticket and ask them for the above data fix. The more people complaining about it the better.

From the perspective of someone who does not plan to take this class, I realize that the way you guys want to treat those people who have used the swap function is very unfair. They didn't simply add them to the waitlist and got enrolled. They used SWAP. What does that mean? That means all of them were enrolled in another class, and got automatically dropped from that class after they are mistakenly enrolled in 194. At least some of them did not know that it was a bug. Many of you guys have used swap, so you know this. It is reasonable just to assume that you got in because you are EECS/CS and had priority and never bother this again. Now the question comes. If you guys manage to drop all those students and drug them back to the waitlist, what about that previous class that they have previously enrolled in? They cannot get in anymore. For example, a student was enrolled in CS 188, and swapped it with this CS 194, then he or she swapped in. That means the student is dropped from CS 188. If you guys want such students to be back on the waitlist, shouldn't you also give back his position in CS 188? Why should those students just end up having 4 less units (e.g. not able to add 188) during Phase 1 because of some system's bug? As you can tell, this is unfair. It is not those students' fault. So why try to punish them by making them not able to take either of those two classes (one enrolled, one being 194)?

Yeah, I think it would be ideal if they could get back into the classes they were originally in, or at least at the very front of the waitlist. I don't think people here are trying to "punish them by making them not able to take either of those two classes". I think the people here just feel as though they got cheated out of the class because of the bug and want to fix it in any way they can. The way the bug affects the students here is also very unfair and the fact that people could swap in and skip the waitlist is unfair.  For example, if a student decided early on that they wanted to take 194 instead of another class (let's say CS188) and ended up on the waitlist, they are also in the exact same situation as these swapping in students: Not being able to take 194 or 188. For some reason, these students are punished for planning ahead of time rather than swapping. I think it would be the "most fair" if those students were put back into their classes (or put at the very front of the waitlist) and the people on the waitlist for 194 got in. I think the other two alternatives (1. Letting the students stay in after the swap, which is unfair to the people on the waitlist and 2. Putting those students that swapped to the back of the waitlist, which is unfair to those people) are at least equally unfair. i would still say 2 is more fair because there is a good chance that the class they swapped in from was not full.

Agree with Anon right above me. I didn't use swap so I'm still on the waitlist, I'd be in the class if it weren't for people using swap. I dropped CS188 which I was enrolled in so I could waitlist for 194. I didn't use swap, it didn't occur to me to try to use swap for a class that was already hit the reserve and was waitlisting people. People who enrolled via swap AFTER I was added to the waitlist are now in the class, and because of that I might not be able to take either 194 or 188. So the same unfairness cuts both ways as the Anon above me says.

I don't necessarily think they should be moved to the back. If their timestamps are available they could be weaved into the existing waitlist at the appropriate position by sorting: create a timestamp column consisting of time-of-waitlisting for waitlisted students / time-of-enrollment-via-swap for those who bypassed the waitlist; sort everyone by that column). This shouldn't affect any of the first 80 people who enrolled.
Is the bug fixed? I heard my friends said that some could still enroll in 194 by swapping and I'm not sure whether I should still stay on the waitlist or just swap to get enrolled at this time.

I also emailed SIS team but they said that they are looking into the issue and eecs departments manage their own enrollments and will be the one that initiate any corrective actions. What’s the decision of eecs department? The open seats are only 6 now and i’m really worried that i’m Not able to get into the class any more.

This is ridiculous. The SIS team is saying that it is up to the EECS department to initiate corrective action. The EECS department is saying that it is up to SIS to get them the list of students / that it is up to the programmers for the Cal Central team. The Office of the Registrar is unresponsive even though the ticket got forwarded there. Phase 2 has already started. There seems to be no way to escalate. This is just ridiculous.
+1 to the above comment

I don't understand why the students are getting so serious about this.

First of all, do you have concrete evidence that people have gotten into he class if they put it on SWAP? Like do you know someone personally who can tell you so? Or is it just that you are basing your assumption based on what you saw on this Piazza? If its the latter, I'd ask you to reconsider your stance. There have been 1-2 instances of this issue and you cannot even verify that they are true since the people involved posted as anonymous.

I have used the SWAP function multiple times before (and even in this current enrollment cycle) and I've never been enrolled directly. So then what evidence do you have of the existence of this bug?

P.S. Before any personal attacks, I'd like to acknowledge that I'm neither enrolled or waitlisted for this class.
Yes, I know several people who have gotten in through SWAP and have said so. I will not name them here obviously.
+1 I know people who just enrolled into the course during phase 2 because of using swap.

Something is obviously going on. I phased 1 the class on October 17 but by then the class was full and I was put on the waitlist (position #17).  The class was expanded to be enroll 110 students. Since October 17 my waitlist position has not gone down but somehow the class now shows there are 104/110 students as of November 16. I am a senior CS major and do not have a conflict with another class, so how are people who are waitlisted higher up being enrolled? If the waitlist was processed as expected I should have been enrolled in the course already..

Right, the only explanation we have so far is the abuse of the swap feature, which in this situation, allowed people to bypass the waitlist during phase 1. 

Confirmed multiple times by people I know, people other commenters here know, and at least one or two specific Piazza posts where people admitted to using swap to bypass the waitlist. 

I really hope I don't regret doing the ethical thing and not using swap to bypass the waitlist when I had the opportunity and knowledge that doing so would get me into the class. I reported the issue thinking it would get resolved.

Another suggestion is that SIS team should at least fix the swap bug first and then eecs can try to expand the class to 30 more spots so that at least no students are disadvantaged by the bug because they are on the same relative position except for those enrolled by the swap feature. However, the bug should be fixed first otherwise those new seats would be taken away by swapping again.

I think it would by far be the most fair if those students were put back in their original classes since there are students behind the first 30 on the waitlist who should still have priority. Also, expanding a class brings logistical issues such as hiring GSI's and readers. If the students were put back in their original classes, it would be as if the bug didn't happen.
Yeah I agree. That would be the most optimal solution. But it seems like they are not doing anything right now so i’m suggesting that simplier solution which is better than nothing
It is infeasible to put students back to their original classes simply because they would have given away their seat for their original class and someone from the waitlist would then get in..

That is not solution that can be done to reverse the bug. For those saying to put back students in their original classes, you're making an assumption that all those who got in by swapping did so with the intent to act unethically. So, for the people that swapped with the intention of getting in the class, by swapping them back out, you will have disadvantaged them because they will no longer be able to get into 194. Had they known they would be swapped out, they would simply add themselves to the waitlist to begin with! But now, how do you determine who had unethical intent?

TLDR: If you're going to propose a solution to handle the "guilty" students that swapped in, it should not punish students that innocently swapped in.
Yeah, I think at this point you should probably just abuse the bug. There's pretty much almost no chance they're actually going to do anything about this.
Try it and see. It won't work out..
^how do you know? Has someone tried recently and failed?
I haven't tried but it look like there are no available seats anymore. I really wish that I had just abused the bug rather than put my faith in the competency of the Berkeley admin.

I notice that students are being enrolled in the class by I am still staying in the same waitlist position. I am a senior majoring in CS, wouldn't I get priority? I don't have any conflicts. Is this happening to anyone else?
